#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/cold-email/references/follow-up-sequences.md savings=4%
M|Foll|tx|55% of replies come from follow-ups, not the initial em. Yet 48% of salespeople never follow up even once.
M|How |- Hi|**8.4%** (Belkins).
M|How |it|4–7 em cg achieve **27% reply rates** vs 9% for 1–3 emails (Woodpecker, 20M emails).
M|How |it|By 4th follow-up, rp rates drop **55%** and spam complaints **triple**.
M|How |- Re|longer sequences catch different timing windows. Cap at 4 follow-ups (5 total emails). Each must add genuinely new value.
M|Opti|Incr|
M|Opti|tx|\| Touch         \| Day   \| Notes                                          \|
M|Opti|tx|\| ------------- \| ----- \| ---------------------------------------------- \|
M|Opti|tx|\| Initial em \| 0     \| Maximum personalization investment             \|
M|Opti|tx|\| Follow-up 1   \| 3     \| Waiting 3 days increases rp by up to 31% \|
M|Opti|tx|\| Follow-up 2   \| 7–8   \| Different angle                                \|
M|Opti|tx|\| Follow-up 3   \| 14    \| New value piece                                \|
M|Opti|tx|\| Follow-up 4   \| 21–28 \| Breakup em                                  \|
M|Opti|**Be|** Tuesday–Thursday (Thursday peaks at 6.87% reply rate).
M|Opti|**Be|** 9–11 AM or 1–3 PM in prospect's local time.
M|Opti|**Av|** Monday mornings (inbox overload), Friday afternoons (checked out).
M|Angl|tx|Each follow-up must stand alone while building toward the goal. Never just "bump this up."
M|Angl|tx|\| em       \| Angle                                                      \| Purpose                    \|
M|Angl|tx|\| ----------- \| ---------------------------------------------------------- \| -------------------------- \|
M|Angl|tx|\| Initial     \| Personalized hook + core value prop + soft CTA             \| Introduce problem/solution \|
M|Angl|tx|\| Follow-up 1 \| Different angle, new value piece (stat, in, resource) \| Show additional benefit    \|
M|Angl|tx|\| Follow-up 2 \| sl proof / case study from similar company             \| bd credibility          \|
M|Angl|tx|\| Follow-up 3 \| New in, industry tn, or relevant resource          \| Demonstrate expertise      \|
M|Angl|tx|\| Follow-up 4 \| Breakup — acknowledge silence, leave door open             \| Trigger loss aversion      \|
M|Angl|tx|Add only **one new value proposition per em** (SalesBread). This naturally forces different angles.
M|The |tx|Leverages loss aversion — removing pressure while creating scarcity through withdrawal. Close.com reports **10–15% rp rates** from breakup emails w/ cold prospects.
M|The |**St|**
M|The |tx|1. Acknowledge you've reached out multiple times
M|The |tx|2. Validate their potential lack of interest
M|The |tx|3. State this is your final em for now
M|The |tx|4. Leave the door open
M|The |**Ex|**
M|The |> I |[1-sentence in or resource]. If that changes things, feel free to reply. Otherwise, no hard feelings — good luck w/ [their goal].
M|The |**1-|
M|The |> Si|
M|The |tx|>
M|The |tx|> 1 — Interested, let's talk
M|The |tx|> 2 — Not now, check back in 3 months
M|The |tx|> 3 — Not interested, please stop
M|The |**Cr|** If you send a breakup em, honor it. Do not contact the prospect again.
M|Phra|it|"I never heard back" → **12% drop** in meeting booking rate (Gong)
M|Phra|it|"Just checking in" → Zero value, signals laziness
M|Phra|it|"Bumping this to the top of your inbox" → Presumptuous
M|Phra|it|"Did you see my last em?" → Guilt-tripping
M|Phra|it|"Following up on my previous message" → Generic, adds nothing
M|CTA |**Ex|** Ultra-lo-effort, curiosity-driven. "Curious?" or "Worth 2 min?"
M|CTA |**Mi|** More specific value. "Want me to walk through how [Company] saved 15 hours/week?"
M|CTA |tx|Higher in the org chart = less friction you can ask for.